[EncDescription_data/units/car/fr/unic_p107]
Adolf Kegresse, who headed the Russian Emperor’s Garage until 1917, developed a new type of propulsive device for cars and trucks in 1909. He replaced the rear axle of a vehicle with a tracked propulsive device, which considerably boosted its cross-country capability. Kegresse returned to France in 1918 and offered his ideas to a few companies. In the end, the Citroen company got interested in the designer’s work, and this resulted in an entire family of semi-trucked vehicles. The rubber-metal track was a specialty of Kegresse’s propulsive device, though the component was not initially distinguished for advanced reliability. 
The French military got interested in Citroen-Kegresse vehicles, and the P.17 artillery tractor was the first Citroen-Kegresse to enter the French army’s inventory. This was followed by the commissioning of the P.19, developed for cavalry. The P.107 model was designed in 1936, but it was becoming more and more obvious that Citroen could not execute a large-scale order on its own. As a result, the P.107 model was manufactured not only by Citroen, but also by other companies. The vehicle was assembled by the Laffly company under the designation of S15T, but the highest number of semi-track tractors was manufactured by the UNIC company. Over 3,000 UNIC P.107 vehicles of various versions were made before 1940. Alongside with artillery tractors, the UNIC P.107 model for engineer forces and another one for airfields were produced. 
The UNIC P.107 was the main type of French medium artillery tractors. Vehicles of this type were most often used for towing the 75-mm Canon de Campagne Mle.1897 guns, as well as howitzers. Many UNIC P.107 vehicles were used by the Wehrmacht after France was defeated. The Germans derived a high number of specialized hardware units from the tractor, starting with APCs and ending with air defense self-propelled systems.

[EncDescription_data/units/car/ger/bmw_r75_w_mg_34]
In the 1930s many European armies were concerned with increasing mobility of the infantry and started introducing sidecar motorcycles. In 1935, the German army set up motorcycle forces, too. They were assigned the mission to deliver three fully equipped soldiers to forward positions in a very short period of time. 
In the first year of the war the army seized motorcycles from civilians for their own purposes. The motorcycles were repainted and duly equipped. As the motorcycles were of various models and companies, and it was next to impossible to obtain spare parts for some of them, these motorcycles did not last longer than a year. This fragility was also the result of operating conditions, as commercial motorcycles were simply not intended for riding through rough terrain in adverse climates. 
November 1937 witnessed talks between the OKH (Army High Command) and the BMW company to produce a heavy cross-country motorcycle with a sidecar for military purposes. 
BMW was ready to offer its solution to the German army already in 1939. This was the prototype of 1934, designed especially for driving in extreme winter weather. It was fitted with a sidecar with a directive wheel, which added to its maneuverability. The telescopic front fork, designed a few years earlier, improved cross-country capabilities of the motorcycle. The frame was composite, which made it possible to easily replace damaged parts. 
In 1941, this motorcycle of impressive exterior, combining excellent maneuverability and advanced produceability, inherent of all BMW models, entered the inventory and was delivered to the front. 
Thanks to easily replaceable parts and smooth controls, the P-75 was very popular and widely used by the German army. It distinguished itself not only in high-speed road travel, but also in crossing streams and making long forced marches on broken country roads. 

[EncDescription_data/units/car/ger/horch_830_b1]
The Horch 830 B1 car was originally intended for commercial use, but was re-equipped for army use in 1937. Most of the manufactured vehicles had canvas covers and cabriolet bodies without doors. The car was produced from 1935 to 1938. The commercial modification differed from the military command car by an all-metal varnished body, chrome-plated bumpers, and doors with crank-operated windows. There were also some modifications in the design of the windshield and windshield wipers. 

[EncDescription_data/units/car/ger/kubelwagen]
In 1936, Ferdinand Porsche started developing a light car for the Army on the basis of the Kdf Typ 60, better known as Volkswagen. The first prototypes, Kdf Typ 62, were made in 1938, and after numerous tests the design went through changes aimed at improving their cross-country capability. Mass-production of the car, designated Kdf Typ 82 and named Kubelwagen, started in December 1939, and the first batch of vehicles was supplied to military units in the spring of 1940. The Kubelwagen gradually became the main light army car. A total of 52,000 vehicles were produced. Alongside with the standard model a variety of modifications were produced: reconnaissance, repair and observation vehicles. The Kubelwagen was also used as a medical car.
Even though the Kubelwagen only had a rear drive gear, the vehicle was distinguished for advanced cross-country capability. Thanks to the simple design and reliability, the car distinguished itself and was very popular in military units.

[EncDescription_data/units/car/ger/opel_blitz_fuel]
The Opel company started manufacturing Opel Blitz 3,6-36S commercial trucks with a cargo capacity of three tonnes in April 1937. They were not designed for the Wehrmacht, but due to an acute shortage of trucks, the vehicles were commissioned. The Wehrmacht started active use of Opel Blitz 3.6-36S trucks in 1940. A total of 82,000 vehicles were manufactured. Alongside with the basic model (side truck), the vehicle was used as a fuel truck for both military units and airfields. In addition, a universal van could be mounted on the vehicle. A medical truck, a communication vehicle and many other varieties were derived from it. A total of about 140 models of this vehicle were designed during the war.
As mentioned above, the Opel Blitz 3,6-36S was not a full-scale army truck. Nevertheless, the vehicle turned out quite fit for military purposes. A single drive gear naturally limited cross-country capability of the Opel Blitz 3,6-36S, but this problem was partially solved with the appearance of the all-wheel-drive model, the Opel Blitz 3,6-6700A. 

