[EncDescription_data/units/car/ger/sdkfz_7]
The Krauss-Maffei AG company started developing a heavy artillery tractor, capable of towing a cargo of eight tonnes, in 1934. Mass production of the vehicle with the factory designation of Krauss-Maffei KM m 8 began later that year. The tractor entered the inventory under the designation of Sd.Kfz.7. The Krauss-Maffei KM m 11, put into production in 1937, became the main model. About 5,000 vehicles were manufactured by Krauss-Maffei and the Borgward company. The Sd.Kfz.7 was also license-produced in Italy by the Breda company under the designation of Breda 61.
Transportation of Flak 18/36/37 air defense guns and sFH 18 heavy howitzers was the main mission of the Sd.Kfz.7. It proved reliable and was popular in military units.

[EncDescription_data/units/car/pol/polish_fiat_pf_508_lazik]
Poland started manufacturing Polski FIAT-508 and FIAT-518 cars and FIAT-614 and FIAT-621 trucks by Italian licenses in the early 1930s. All these vehicles were used in the Polish army for staff, transport, medical and special purposes. 
In late 1935, engineers Mieczysław Skwierczyński and Tadeusz Tański designed the FIAT-508 Lazik military vehicle (its commercial prototype was called Polski FIAT-508 III Junak). The new automobile in comparison to its predecessor had an open body that ensured quick mounting and dismounting of four men with firearms. The body was made of steel with a basic wooden structure in the rear section. The inner side of the body carried special equipment for military purposes, such as bags for hand grenades and cartridges, and mounts for armaments. Some vehicles carried a 7.92-mm Browning wz.28 machine-gun.
About 1,500 Lazik and about 400 tractors derived from the same Junak were manufactured. The latter could tow a trailer weighing up to 350 kg and were intended for transporting a 37-mm antitank gun. 

[EncDescription_data/units/car/pol/polish_fiat_pf_621_tent]
The Polski FIAT 621L was the most common Polish pre-war truck and the basic military truck in 1939. It was an improved and strengthened copy of the Italian FIAT 621, produced in the PZInz works from 1935 to 1939. The PF-621L was a 2.5t truck with a 46 HP engine. In 1938 the new streamlined cab was introduced. From among 9,500 produced before the war, the Army had 1,400 in 1939, not counting the commissioned civilian vehicles. A small number of heavier PF-621R 3-tonne trucks (on a bus chassis) was also used. PF-621s were used as general service trucks, and also as troop carriers in the 10th Motorized Cavalry Brigade (10 BKZmot) and Warsaw Armored-Motorized Brigade (WBP-M).

[EncDescription_data/units/car/rus/gaz_67]
The war between the Soviet Union and Finland of 1939-1940, which took place under extreme winter conditions, exposed the need for a reliable and mobile cross-country vehicle for servicing the Red Army command personnel, headquarters and reconnaissance, as well as for communications and towing light artillery systems.
The NATI institute and the Gorky Automobile Plant (GAZ) received an order to design an army cross-country vehicle.
Development of the new vehicle, designated GAZ-64-416, began on February 3, 1941. Already on April 15-27, the vehicle passed field trials, and its mass production was launched immediately. The first mass-produced GAZ-64-416 vehicles, were delivered to front, by Moscow, in August 1941. At the beginning of the war, the BA-64 light machine-gun vehicle was derived from the GAZ-64 chassis. All in all, the Gorky Automobile Plant manufactured 601 GAZ-64-416 vehicles before the end of 1941. 
Production of an upgraded cross country vehicle, designated GAZ-67 and featuring a broad gauge, redesigned body, reinforced frame, and refined suspension, began in September 1943. 
The automobile was upgraded again in 1944, and the new variety was designated GAZ-67B. About 5,250 GAZ-67 and GAZ-67B vehicles were made during the war, and they became the standard command vehicles of the Red Army.

[EncDescription_data/units/car/rus/gaz_aaa]
Mass production of the GAZ-AAA three-axle truck began at the Gorky Automobile Plant in November 1934. the design of the truck was derived from that of the GAZ-AA vehicle. It was upgraded, i.e. the rear drive axle was replaced with a two-axle trolley. The increase in the number of wheels boosted the automobile’s cross-country capability on tracks and forest roads. The cross-country capability on snow and soft ground could be further improved by adding Overall chains to the rear wheels. 
The GAZ-AA was mostly intended for transporting troops and cargo. Moreover, the GAZ-AAA chassis was used to manufacture BA-6 medium armored vehicles, GAZ-05-193 staff buses, fuel trucks and radar stations. During the war, the three-axle vehicles also carried SU-12 artillery systems, HMG Maxim or HMGs DShK. As many as 37,373 vehicles of this type were made from 1934 to 1943. 

[EncDescription_data/units/car/rus/gaz_m1]
The Gorky Automobile Plant (GAZ) started manufacturing the GAZ-M1 (“Emka”) car in 1936. The car was derived from the Ford-V8-40 vehicle, designed in 1933. However, the prototype was modified by the Gorky Plant’s design department, taking into account lack of proper roads in Russia. The car frame was reinforced, the number of springs was increased from two to four, spoke wheels were replaced with pressed solid wheels, and their diameter was increased. The engine was modified and boosted from 40 to 50 hp. 
Thanks to these improvements, the car became stronger and much more enduring.
The GAZ-M1 vehicle had relatively good speed specifications and could run as fast as 105 km/h on the highway. Average fuel consumption amounted to 14.5 l per 100 km. The GAZ-M1 was designed as a commercial vehicle, but its cross-country capability on unpaved roads was advanced enough to derive the BA-20 armored vehicle from it. 
The GAZ-M1 was in production until 1943. A total of 62,888 vehicles of this type were manufactured, most of them staying in service with the Red Army until the end of the war. Quite a lot of models were derived from the GAZ-M1. 

[EncDescription_data/units/car/rus/nkl_16_mod_1941]
The first variant of the three-ski NKL-16 snowmobile was made in 1937 under the supervision of chief designer Nikolai Andreyev. The snowmobile was mass-produced as transport and medical models. An updated model was manufactured in 1940-1941. It had four skis and was designated NKL-16/41.
The snowmobiles of all manufactured types, including NKL-16, NKL-16/41 and NKL-16/42, were widely employed at fronts of the Great Patriotic War, especially in the winter of 1941-1942. They were used for quick communication, delivery of military cargo, reconnaissance, assault and combat missions. When delivering assault groups, the snowmobiles not only carried servicemen with full armament, but also towed 18 to 20 skiers, using special cables. In combat conditions, they towed sledges at the sides, carrying soldiers armed with a MG and a soldier with ammo. Moreover, machine-gun fire could be delivered by soldiers sitting in the snowmobile through hatches located at the top.
Snowmobile transport battalions successfully accomplished numerous intelligence and communication missions of the Soviet Army command and worked with combat snowmobile units, using NKL-26 vehicles. This made it possible not only to make unexpected raids aimed at destroying enemy infantry, but also to quickly deliver assault groups.

[EncDescription_data/units/car/rus/voroshilovetz]
The introduction of powerful artillery systems in the Red Army in the mid-1930s, as well as the emergence of new medium and heavy tanks weighing up to 28 tons, made it necessary to design a powerful tractor. The Kharkov Locomotive-Building Plant received the order to design and manufacture such a tractor in 1935. 
Two tractors were already produced in 1936 and underwent factory and field tests in the next two years. In March 1937 one of them was demonstrated to the Soviet government and received highest approval. Mass production of the “Voroshilovets” began in 1939. About 800 vehicles were made before the beginning of the Great Patriotic War, 228 of them were handed over to the artillery. Another 170 were manufactured during wartime. 
During the war “Voroshilovets” tractors were used quite effectively on all fronts, for transportation of heavy cargo, but primarily heavy artillery.

[EncDescription_data/units/car/rus/zis_5]
In 1939, the Stalin Automobile Plant (Moscow) started manufacturing the ZIS-5 truck that was used both before the war and during the war as a transport vehicle, artillery tractor and as chassis for various specialized vehicles. The number of ZIS-5 trucks in the army exceeded 140,000 on the eve of the war. 
The ZIS-5 was a derivative of the АМО-2 and АМО-3 trucks, which design was based on the Autocar truck. The new truck’s engine, metal two-seat cabin and wooden platform with a cargo capacity of three tons were mounted on an elastic frame that functioned as a spring when the automobile was moving throughbroken terrain. 
The ZIS-5 was fitted with a six-cylinder gasoline engine with a capacity of 5,555 cubic centimeters, developing 73 hp. The engine was started by an electric starter or manually with the help of a crank arm. The fuel tank with a capacity of 60 liters was located under the driver’s seat. Fuel range on a highway reached 205 km. 
The ZIS-5 was manufactured until October 15, 1941, when the Moscow-based ZIS plant was closed, and relocation of its shops to the east began. Production of the military modification, named ZIS-5V, began in Miass and Ulyanovsk in April 1942. The ZIS-5V featured a wooden cabin, welded G-shaped wings, a wooden cargo platform with a folding side, and wooden footboard instead of metal ones. Some vehicles of this variety featured a steering wheel with wooden casing, instead of ebonite. 
The ZIS-5 and its military modification ZIS-5V were distinguished for advanced reliability and easy technical maintenance and repairs. The ZIS-5V was manufactured by automobile plants in Ulyanovsk and Miass during the war, and its production at the Moscow-based ZIS plant was launched in June 1942. About 83,000 trucks were manufactured from May 1942 to May 1945. 

